"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:3.2.2\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">3.2.2</span> Tent peg, stake</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">יָתֵד</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(yathed)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod27:19\">EXO 27:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod27:19\">EXO 27:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod35:18\">EXO 35:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod35:18\">EXO 35:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod38:20\">EXO 38:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod38:31\">EXO 38:31</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod38:31\">EXO 38:31</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:40\">EXO 39:40</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num3:37\">NUM 3:37</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num4:32\">NUM 4:32</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg4:21\">JDG 4:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg4:21\">JDG 4:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg4:22\">JDG 4:22</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg5:26\">JDG 5:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra9:8\">EZR 9:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa33:20\">ISA 33:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa54:2\">ISA 54:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech10:4\">ZEC 10:4</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">πάσσαλος</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(passalos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir14:24\">SIR 14:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir26:12\">SIR 26:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir27:2\">SIR 27:2</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0411_loop_in_rope_en.jpg\" alt=\"Peg, loop in rope\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Peg, loop in rope (Source unknown)</figcaption></figure>The tent peg was a shortened stick, pointed on one end. It was driven into the ground, and tent ropes were tied to it to anchor the tent in place. See the illustrations at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">3.2 Tent&lt;REALIA:3.2&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The stakes of the Tabernacle, mentioned in Exodus and Numbers, were made of bronze. They were used to anchor the various coverings of the Tabernacle (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">3.15.2.3.6 Coverings&lt;REALIA:3.15.2.3.6&gt;</a>) and also some of the standing posts (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">3.15.2.3.3 Upright beam, tenon, crosspiece, rung&lt;REALIA:3.15.2.3.3&gt;</a>).</p>\n<p>The tent stake provided security. It guaranteed that the tent would not fall nor be blown out of its place by winds. Thus it is sometimes a symbol of stability and security. This element of security may be reflected in translation in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra9:8\">EZR 9:8</a> and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa33:20\">ISA 33:20</a>; for example, in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra9:8\">EZR 9:8</a> the literal clause “to give us a tent peg within the place of his holiness” is rendered by <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> as “to give us a secure hold within his holy place,” and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> has “live in safety in this holy place.”</p>\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0412_tent_pegs_en.jpg\" alt=\"Tent pegs\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Tent pegs (Don Ellens, The Tabernacle of Israel, Harris, Jones 1888, Public domain)</figcaption></figure>or another sense of the Hebrew word <em>yathed</em> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg16:14\">JDG 16:14</a>, see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.5.3.5 Beater, batten, pin&lt;REALIA:1.5.3.5&gt;</a>.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir14:24\">SIR 14:24</a>: The Greek word <em>passalos</em> refers to a tent peg. The Hebrew version of Sirach has a word that, with a very slight emendation of part of one letter, could mean “tent cords” or “tent pegs.” With either reading, the basic meaning remains the same and is expressed well by <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>: “Camp as close to her house as you can get.” If translators wish to maintain the image of the tent and the house, they may say “he attaches his tent to the wall of her house.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
